rsonal accumulation of goods or power. These lifeworlds were shattered by colonialism, capitalist development, and cultural imperialism in the twentieth century. Based on two decades of ethnographic field research, Truly Human portrays these peoples’ lifeworlds, teachings, political struggles for recognition, and relations with non-human animals. Taking seriously their ontological claims that Gaya offers moral guidance to all humans, Scott E. Simon reflects on what this particular form of Indigenous resurgence reveals about human rights, sovereignty, and the good of all kind. Truly Human contributes to a decolonizing anthropology at a time when all humans need Indigenous land-based teachings more than ever.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnologyzTaiwan. 0aTaiwan aborigines. 0aTruku (Taiwan people) 0aTruku (Taiwan people). 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aFormosa.  aIndigenous peoples.  aIndigenous resurgence.  aIndigenous-state relations.  aTaiwan.  aindigeneity.  alegal pluralism.  amulticulturalism.  aontologies.  aphilosophy.  apolitical anthropology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754954140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487549541423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487549541/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles